## Using the Accounts API to Retrieve Balances

The Accounts API provides secure access to customer account information, including real\-time balance details. This guide demonstrates how to authenticate with the banking system, make a request to the balance endpoint, and interpret the response. By following these steps, you can easily integrate account balance checks into your applications.

## Steps for integration

1. **Authenticate**
  Obtain an OAuth 2.0 token using your client credential.

  ```text
  curl -X POST "https://api.bankexample.com/oauth2/token" \\
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \\
  -d "grant_type=client_credentials&client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID&client_secret=YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET"
  ```

  The response will include an access\_token youâ€™ll use in the next step.
1. **Make the Balance Request**
  Once authenticated, call the balance endpoint.

  ```text
  curl -X GET "<https://api.bankexample.com/v1/accounts/123456789/balance?currency=USD>" \\
  -H "Authorization: Bearer ACCESS_TOKEN"
  ```

  The response will include an access\_token youâ€™ll use in the next step.
1. **Handle the Response**
  A successful response looks like this:

  ```text
  {
    "accountId": "123456789",
    "currency": "USD",
    "balance": 2450.75,
    "availableBalance": 2200.00,
    "lastUpdated": "2025-09-18T09:30:00Z"
  }
  ```

  The response will include an access\_token youâ€™ll use in the next step.

  - balance: Total account balance.
  - availableBalance: Funds available to spend/withdraw.
  - lastUpdated: Timestamp when the balance was last refreshed.
1. **Handle Errors**
  The response will include an access\_token youâ€™ll use in the next step.

  - If you see 401 Unauthorized, check your token validity.
  - If you see 404 Account Not Found, confirm the accountId exists.
  - If you see 429 Too Many Requests, implement retry logic with exponential backoff.
